        {
            "title": "Letters That Sound the Same?",
            "description": "Some Hebrew letters look very similar but sound different depending on a dot (called a dagesh) or the dot’s position (as in Shin and Sin). In this lesson, you'll learn to tell them apart using pronunciation and example words.",
            "cards": [
                {
                    "class": "vocab",
                    "qlang": "default",
                    "vocab": {
                        "בּ (Bet, with dagesh) – as in בַּיִת (bayit - house)": "בּ",
                        "ב (Vet, without dagesh) – as in לֵב (lev - heart)": "ב",
                        "כּ (Kaf, with dagesh) – as in כֶּלֶב (kelev - dog)": "כּ",
                        "כ (Khaf, without dagesh) – as in מֶלֶךְ (melekh - king)": "כ",
                        "שׁ (Shin, right dot, /ʃ/) – as in שָׁלוֹם (shalom)": "שׁ",
                        "שׂ (Sin, left dot, /s/) – as in שָׂמֵחַ (sameach)": "שׂ"
                    }
